<table role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td><div style="height:20px;line-height:20px"> </div></td></tr></tbody></table><!--[if mso | IE]><tr><td class="" width="600px" ><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="" role="presentation" style="width:600px;" width="600" ><tr><td style="line-height:0px;font-size:0px;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;"><![endif]--><div style="margin:0px auto;max-width:600px;"><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="width:100%;"><tbody><tr><td style="border:1px solid #DCDCDC;direction:ltr;font-size:0px;padding:0;padding-top:0px;text-align:center;"><!--[if mso | IE]><table role="presentation" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td class="" style="vertical-align:top;width:598px;" ><![endif]--><div class="mj-column-per-100 mj-outlook-group-fix" style="font-size:0px;text-align:left;direction:ltr;display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:100%;"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" width="100%"><tbody><tr><td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" width="100%"><tbody><tr><td align="left" style="background:#FFFFFF;font-size:0px;padding:16px 16px 0;word-break:break-word;"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%" border="0" style="color:#000000;font-family:Georgia, serif;font-size:13px;line-height:22px;table-layout:auto;width:100%;border:none;"><tr><td valign="top"><span style="font-size:24px;font-style:italic;font-family:Georgia, serif;font-weight:400;line-height:140%;color:#052962">Katharine Viner, editor-in-chief</span></td><td width="110" height="90" style="line-height:0;font-size:0"><img src="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9assuTJHoR_xtxJtNZ-864UlvZLM79Q3QOEkl8XNCRTvcjWNlmqs6eSaPn1MkZUcl_EJeaofBd_zH_5Kc1BJLl-Et3JLKEfPREyYryvnbkyeHX4FFTjesTP-IQMlUt5PBqfQ4D7U5y4fJt74hrupNwReoUHXqCTjgB7FBhR2d8SfYt7_vZ3GrYu0f2Offt526fQ/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t3/h001.wcHJ5GN-MiTSsUBEeMiq040mVMxwcBJvnzv_WTg4dKc alt="Katharine Viner, editor-in-chief" width="110" height="90"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td style="border-top:2px dashed;border-top-color:#999999;background-color:#FFFFFF;padding-bottom:8px"> </td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="text" style="background:#FFFFFF;font-size:0px;padding:0 16px;word-break:break-word;"><div style="font-family:Georgia, serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:400;line-height:22px;text-align:left;color:#121212;"><p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0;">It was a jaw-dropping slip with potentially far reaching ramifications. The fallout from US national security adviser, Mike Waltz, adding Atlantic editor-in-chief, Jeffrey Goldberg to the now infamous “Houthi PC small group” Signal chat continues. This week we’ve focused on the political response in the US and the global security implications for the rest of us.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Archie Bland, <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBNfMDKFRfOEsk3CaiO1OPbbgg_OXtW_2reS7Y3OQzvUuQMP5UlZolJF_Mwou4zSQjOCL0yizTxddT602UHXJ77E9Cldq85JncKwViocluc88rVFg9E8auhrZeF7IKSsYCRavzjmm7H6Tsv2_J9VFRq0okKTTXRubemjN7OPgvXfMwp9d3lm__7ySs36v-NGSdd_FarbLVY34J9M3mMXmrJIEVADOPD6ChtbFyPGZvtuy2ceOK7GuaG80zU9Bt0EJ2V1aayvbyiZ-U8mQEnR4lI9DK9ulNa6OqCi_SF-CDmuUg/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t4/h001.3NgYhoWs_S3ysBOYrH6V6GlXfHpDl0qThltljHxwiSI style="color: #0077B6;">for the essential First Edition newsletter</a>, asked just how bad the leak was and looked at the security implications of using Signal for national security discussions. Media columnist Margaret Sullivan <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPmb_62cBCcT0p1ftGfLF2PDD6zMXs8OJDLlGHveHrDrYLUbJEZq_pLaw6ymTZEGac_b0PgRHMjrjWcd0ZM1Y7FNS1CSxKnpwpTfaTJhu67-xSL88PISRKfbO8iex1qI9SjNV70btvKRVvCjk0-AzKo_A3B9eCCqL7QhAInZlI3O0QPe0DgR_83adGn_fGsKwPekWb22RGD-uRdpdbapvppapUWRVwaIiTZUzF_vMldCGDcRFKYmewEU_pnJCLOuHm-cTCiik-UrTqiceVqe-QCO7wv2NRKF3upHw5uESlaLw/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t5/h001.hxMDVOoqSa5tHOLgp-OjIeq9AOdBoGwbd3tckC-QgzU style="color: #0077B6;">praised the Atlantic’s handling of an extraordinary leak</a> and Robert Tait <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBO2xZEcDhZvi30zK70agsnuNdppovOgnqKwU6CA9U2apRMAtlO0t1LvJ2dLerFpPBZe74w3VvNnV40-l73VlYA6vYCxnnc5ZCn7wyjCwnGmhBQTAyLMsf0frOqjxl0AmCdUBdmodsR5Ul0sd5FwueW7UwKnACUJ9WUCJM4BfocIUEcagqWtry3MfSrzpwpoKpebYn62ysyB-Q9dcEby8KDAGRWGWjOJujo-vWkT144OsqmWiHNTWB5HQxHmkujkmx0_gGlkDS5dzZ0XA2vfVxHb/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t6/h001.9Q0YvxuqnG-eUvCWHmeK7vOpxHO-1E6Ip4_0DMa49NI style="color: #0077B6;">profiled Goldberg</a> who, since breaking the story, has been the subject of a stream of ad hominem attacks from some of the officials on the Signal thread. Jonathan Freedland and Susan B Glasser discussed how Trump himself had blamed the media, rather than Waltz and company, <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPywq5DlRSL8szX-TRfUc_yvDFRqzgJvnbfDQNtXQEJR8z-BPeovfQP5Ej4s8rd91NP6PSPlDMF_OGi95BwNVt1XI7Jtbqlec-XgXWLjuR51kXQ20dzkUNTnCl26XP-n17oP4EeafOFXHd8Os8KfAfhwq8kqeR__xnDEKWRitKGq8bVt2YR-JIVyNMlky4q37GmqnpfGLiwpxsBLzEN2Dms27WTWxryO9DD-IW1q_EC7dA3E_-8WFBtzxN_luYAMQJZBgFLTibiNvftdc-2kD6s/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t7/h001._3szPTzw8dVanSBg3iRb4nDmc4ZixTrqrm8mAc2wmAI style="color: #0077B6;">on the Politics Weekly America podcast</a>. Meanwhile, senior international correspondent Peter Beaumont looked both at <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBO2xZEcDhZvi30zK70agsnuTy7TuY9RN0eb8tyhtpMaoiXd_3CYcXy1G4w-Syu3gJTiZojGFrfBZMn7g2Ueffe-gmMpEbla15dl4Xz0l_4ghkBQMoLI3oUnVt0Sx_VXKqbN994G2ROKmWqyijoKBEMVB3Mf2XRSEuC5xF64qZFct_OI011GAG91xIfO1G8gpT5Ekhs8-7YL_L6BTyju5kSpRUELGY9GGTKz43KEP8jY_qIsza2-jufeTyH3ykErXWtATuRRgGJzXf-fGJCTZ3uF/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t8/h001.iWbODHXS_RzTu5qNIfBiELvpJTdqnETHwl9zRA5h98Y style="color: #0077B6;">what hostile states could take away from the leak</a> and how some of the participants’ lies and denials about the messages have <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBO2xZEcDhZvi30zK70agsnuf9CWr8Ugh2yjTY45qeB73brq9dnrQoHa666xy3sFh24LaojwcbK4LAFbJ2jQxNaKa5WagRj1_AZ1QpdyxdPLkmFngO_cyR1E6iHN5jk1GhFNzj3ijRYY7zANiObhkWbbHi4OAYJHUHy7xNTX39RZ__MnxCbXAflhEx5SI3agrTLH66i9Htex-qIln1oelzqOmAYe0PshE-y6aT4vx9hadGTg4AQYIPtDHDKzSGoapIb6NCrsP2fNMkUebJR6AKn5/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t9/h001._aHiZvsXqeQU0DzvLQioR0ON3ymgF7y82874V5SLYGg style="color: #0077B6;">“made the scandal immeasurably more serious than it was already”</a>.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0;">That point was elaborated on by Joseph Gedeon and Hugo Lowell, in the Washington team, who wrote that the biggest problem with the leak wasn’t only that sensitive military operations were revealed, but <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBO2xZEcDhZvi30zK70agsnu_D4gaUu3_KTAf1B47k-R2uszz1YPkHDHNg_BkG13lBQD_pC9CbyHx26DDeCmBEsbS_uZ1Y2lt3f3cIUQRBuFQKUepKg3j7jL8bBaihsbixxV7OOtKRQFM9DMmeAI1_LTOjw4N5-ceayhFF7ceYA2mQbC-Uu79b2f854iNsMZc3mQ0a6NCBnVgIz9WKJm-AKDlcvCE3m8-BjE4JEpGuMi-CAOiTAZGuSDLIL79j1woic/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t10/h001.gUeXnXZqe5e4BegnhXajry-MAEdT2wOYaHFrMw7lZJ8 style="color: #0077B6;">the systemic dishonesty it revealed</a>: “It exposes a system of broken accountability, where high-ranking officials can spill military secrets with apparent near-total immunity.” While that was the public response, columnist Moira Donegan was cutting on what the messages said about t<a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPmb_62cBCcT0p1ftGfLF2PjNQh6aMrHvkxc61dBLCgDgZGOUy6VPC5STcdbuU4rHbZPE8OQHhau457C6_xESRAvC4e8O3bcqQ9OCi4WUrafTGD_DWCGeqQINJJctoIW-6CW-jS_lym8mNNM01frfkpyJ8xVZcG0BsRj_fB-DVvkxF9qWuhOQ084ZhJT0G4CRkN3ylOrIdggtU5IckbAPTm5VR_YjYdAVAElFOpqjvCSTwhJcHv3Vh5iB324JhjWJxymOC47AZ-T1RRr7zK6NfO/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t11/h001.ihnQTWVhXxP9yWR-OfBr69yHXP9KlSdzCsuks91d3zE style="color: #0077B6;">he private behaviour of these top officials</a>: “The group chat speaks to the essence of the second Trump administration: its cavalier incompetence, its contempt for human life.”</p><p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0;">For those of us outside the United States, the attitudes – to information security and towards supposed allies – were the most troubling takeaways from the debacle. Leyland Cecco and Eva Corlett asked what it meant for the <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBO2xZEcDhZvi30zK70agsnutoIWJgCzBn_35TX6XEp3rXp1VFvKIknA0LIat0oEIB0V-nxJAzmliDqAHp0UrBph5ctEp_9NcmEFB219R7HwoH5MgiaEJLDpRDfPTgE2zem_1UNGyLSftsJYiFtphT23jaDaZI5QIJey7tfOkvY6yvv_tVUuyY6pWevtXXS7SsBNRShEEJe3sLdyfqrVNjtFWs6EK1MxzfPMx_Bu3mvnYdtmbWwCbhwGVMoNRgb9E_p6YTeeyfMTX2YblhFbJM6i/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t12/h001.WjXKELzkj_JbABKr1MwLuQE8xVsT9LTjzX589qB4Y2Y style="color: #0077B6;">future of the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing</a> alliance, while Andrew Roth analysed <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBNfMDKFRfOEsk3CaiO1OPbbbjdgbYfFIQEChDo7lXLFt_qNRmv6wpiLr3SdbF591cO0uE-Lv68OwbNc9bBhidxyxZub66oYCMTYKpsNh85mSbr5Esf51J5AQTg5nUvF7hv2s7Dk3spWqZZu46ctiBKCJLHxy7SQZtKEOKA5Hmq7K5Yah5wCYRwwji7_ugg4152g8WaQ-CYcODgNwydVjuUUykzX1-ekPymHeLl0oM3ig7lzTA2wU325r6q-huSyZt7T7fEW_DLC5s3ws3EmQNy0IJxXTPSl2GKMOiTOfy8cyPQ7sEzm3TnttjxS1WL5kZ4/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t13/h001.i6pqpEezPYw8o2-84zhDL2lciip5yX40HOj19TbIS7k style="color: #0077B6;">how the messages revealed</a> the sheer level of contempt in which the likes of JD Vance and Pete Hegseth hold Europe. As columnist <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPmb_62cBCcT0p1ftGfLF2PzMWEY0qzmrOHXc-9vRflpDEem8ft2YpqpWlwoT5_ltEAnFa1eNRbEJpWQWcENkIM5s4wlDRP8aTHeeZ7ck5pequQHtcuuQ8wbj7VCPXd9rR32R6_wk6Bn7Mf12XaAVNHiUoUcxcL3-98lwI3vZxZdVkEz-bC5ggHNz-8pBmYaaXmQFeBOZ_lHfg81WVB7APD2ZE-DvNphcODdSqbMenzQwqn1lFuGGkdS6Cccxvho37yPYlty39Zs2lM6f4VRKO4uCvR9DBtQFU0PR9llvJSBQ/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t14/h001.SaPEqYBv-JK_07nifs3Mn0MnUmPAJIg2IcfLKaHmqMY style="color: #0077B6;">Marina Hyde put it</a>, “Please enjoy European diplomats declaring that as far as the relationship between the continent and the US goes, this is ‘the writing on the wall’. If only it HAD been written on a wall – that would actually have been more secure and secretive.”</p><p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Another quiet week in American politics, then. For help keeping in the loop, our team in the US produces a daily catchup of events in American politics that readers tell us they are finding very useful indeed. (You can <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBMyAEbCrOvS-sO1EQcFQ3Xj0fJpop8eH5CwYSxREPmFmVugHap54ZeY41tiOOoJLh2_EPGsyKPRn5Fmcr7W-JpATYKDcdBTGIScMnu3yQrWr5ZhS0LjracnARYa7iYhwYQElNuCSMQQ0aE4U1ALmZOfPtA9FbTxqk2_TYEoZAEk3tEpd5YMMXDUUIOQ_biZYgFk9-xjMK93DDDY1e9M3iS4gt4ikb_-mPpxGI34GusSRk185dyruyazP6IZ6O1gAjM/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t15/h001.s3GN-iSXfJitZupR1O7HLx3F_2cIOC00eec4OVpHNrc style="color: #0077B6;">bookmark it here</a>.) And do keep an eye on <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPihAwchbmyCFa_i54vpQhDiVcgE5d7pmXHkdXARG3MpNO_lWJNvtdmJ3DiayPnkHtrYIS1U_kKaPKO1s8W7cOe8qhyvoSXXajS4rqNRYE33Cbp8l7vfpZCIeLLa_meLnvKxBEG_ZeQcUc0sRIFhnKQAv8GQ3YT1tvdvxLog7U5h1bQTeIhU_Xu5-ERSPaPmN1tCCmf60si_5FbemK8psYmonRoQZ3NjFSaHuTuCA6s-Q/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t16/h001.V-AR2k-BL50qi6ivNDWMBIqhLgje5sryaDqH9z_fX4o style="color: #0077B6;">Opt out</a>, a series in which Johana Bhuiyan helps readers to safely navigate your online privacy, which is more important than ever. (And which is perhaps one for Mike Waltz to bookmark … ) This week’s edition explains how green card holders and foreign visitors <a href="https://ablink.editorial.theguardian.com/ss/c/u001.-maoMBGKBrIn6te6KzY9apUCjm_UVImAPea-qhHewBPJwPsWIxzAvlsDY32xjO2ctze-Ac0h1GUvGmp1u8V7fMZsvtpHhqbPNjNQmECIqmYx-kNsNcakpMObGYpiSjMCysZ9noEuZGDvsyhOoZJLXAxbsvJcOzE6KNpAtjjc1SPKnoLoDGWkfyAukRaeGrz__PpmgKKDmw_gl8mHyqYHP2WkY77T4Ct_Qx1HXlwt0mykpHT5gZu3oprSyv5pH3H1Ll_o4RbOMivRsJgHHTsRkFdlp9LnwhXllgczO4xCW3p79_lO8QbAuUbOlHBwLJv4/4f7/u907YvKMT92Se6lYyXvnTw/t17/h001.NoCVr4jNHv8PQgnYfNWY_zTTsRGXXZknPduBfjH0Lqw style="color: #0077B6;">can protect their phone data</a> from overzealous officials at the US border.</p></div></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></div><!--[if mso | IE]></td></tr></table><![endif]--></td></tr></tbody></table></div><!--[if mso | IE]></td></tr></table></td></tr><![endif]--> <!-- Braze Placeholder - Above Section 2 --><table role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td><div style="height:20px;line-height:20px"> </div></td></tr></tbody></table><!--[if mso | IE]><tr><td class="" width="600px" ><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="" role="presentation" style="width:600px;" width="600" ><tr><td style="line-height:0px;font-size:0px;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;"><![endif]--><div style="margin:0px auto;max-width:600px;"><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="width:100%;"><tbody><tr><td style="border:1px solid #DCDCDC;border-top:none;direction:ltr;font-size:0px;padding:0;text-align:center;"><!--[if mso | IE]><table role="presentation" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td class="" style="vertical-align:top;width:598px;" ><![endif]--><div class="mj-column-per-100 mj-outlook-group-fix" style="font-size:0px;text-align:left;direction:ltr;display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:100%;"><table border="0" cellpadding="0